⠀⡇⠠⠐⠀⠹⣕⣄⠂⠠⠁⠠⠁⢂⠈⠄⠂⢀⣂⣽⠷⠚⠙⠉⠉⢁⠠⠀⠌⠀⠄⡁⠠⢀⣡⠟⠀⠀⠀⠘⢿⣿⡿⣿⣟⡿⣽⣷⣿⣻⢷⣻⣞⡷⣯⣟⡿⡇⠀⠀
⠀⠻⡤⠂⠁⠄⠈⠙⢦⣆⡁⠐⡈⠀⠄⢂⠈⠖⠉⠀⡀⠐⢈⠠⠁⠂⠠⢈⠠⠈⡀⢐⣠⠞⠁⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⢸⣿⣽⣳⢿⣻⡿⣽⢾⡽⣯⢷⣯⣟⡷⣯⢿⡇⠀⠀                                                                                                  
                                                                                                      
                                                                                                
   Logs                                                                                                           



/var/log/syslog -or- /var/log/messages 

Stores all global system activity data, including startup messages. 
Debian-based systems like Ubuntu store this in /var/log/syslog.
Redhat-based systems like RHEL or Centos store this in /var/log/messages.

========================================

/var/log/auth.log -or- /var/log/secure 

Stores logs from the pluggable authentication module (pam) including successful logins, failed login attempts, and authentication methods.
Ubuntu and Debian store authentication messages in /var/log/auth.log.
Redhat and Centos store this data in /var/log/secure.  Solaris stores data in /var/adm.

=========================================

dmesg

Kernel logs in memory, often seen in /var/log/messages or the equivalent.

If it logs as critical in syslog.conf, it is probably going to be in dmesg too.

============================================

/var/log/kern 

Stores kernel error and warning data, which is particularly helpful for troubleshooting custom kernels.
This may not be extremely important to you as a basic operator, but it will be later on… don’t you worry!

============================================

/var/log/cron 

Stores information about cron jobs. Use this data to verify that your cron jobs are running successfully.
Which file has the setting for where cron is explicitly configured to place its log?
Which file will contain my cron messages such as errors?

============================================

How do Linux system log files get created? 

The answer is through the syslog daemon, which listens for log messages on the syslog socket /dev/log and then writes them to the appropriate log file.

Applications also write log files in this directory. For example, popular servers like Apache, Nginx, MySQL, and more can write log files here.
Some of these log files are written by the application itself. 
Others are created through syslog.

